Even if an experimental vaccine seems so far able to reduce the mortality rate of Ebola, no treatment has yet been sufficiently effective to treat existing infection.
Even though the administration of a cocktail of antibodies, ZMapp, had initially shown promising signs on the ground, formal studies have shown that its ability to limit deaths did not meet expectations.
In the PALM trial, ZMapp was used as a control, meaning that the scientists used it as a baseline and compared it to the three other treatments.
The United States Olympic Committee supports the letter of the United States Olympic Committee and accepts the absolute necessity of the Olympic family to promote a safe environment for all our athletes.
We agree with the USOC's statement that the interests of our athletes and clubs, as well as their sport, could be better served. This can be done by moving forward and making significant changes within our organization, rather than revoking accreditation.
USA Gymnastics supports an independent investigation that could shed light on how the abuse described so courageously by the survivors of Larry Nassar could have gone unnoticed for so long and adopts any necessary and appropriate changes.
USA Gymnastics and the USOC share the same goal: to make gymnastics, and other sports, as safe as possible so that athletes can pursue their dreams in a safe, positive and responsible environment.
Throughout the 1960s, Brzezinski worked for John F. Kennedy as a counselor, then for the administration of Lyndon B. Johnson.
During the 1976 selection, he advised Carter on foreign policy, then was National Security Advisor (NSA) from 1977 to 1981, succeeding Henry Kissinger.
During his time at the NSA, he helped Carter resolve international issues such as the Camp David Accords in 1978, the normalization of relations between the United States and China in the late 1970s, the Iranian Revolution and its consequences such as the Iran hostage crisis in 1979, and the Soviet invasion of Afghanistan in 1979.
