This confirms not only that at least some dinosaurs had feathers, a theory that is already very widespread, but provides details that fossils can generally not provide, such as color and three-dimensional arrangement.
Scientists say that the plumage of this animal was chestnut brown on top and pale or carotenoid in color on the bottom.
This discovery also helps to better understand the evolution of feathers in birds.
Given that dinosaur feathers do not have a fully developed shaft, which is called a rachis, but do show other characteristics of feathers – barbs and barbules – researchers have deduced that the rachis was probably a later evolutionary development than these other characteristics.
The structure of the feathers suggests they were not used for flight but rather for temperature regulation or display. The researchers suggested that, even if it is the tail of a young dinosaur, the specimen shows an adult plumage and not the down of a chick.
Scientists say it is the tail of a juvenile dinosaur, but the specimen reveals a feathering that belongs to an adult, not a young one.
